			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Fantasy Books with Bards (Recommendations, please)<a name="29931"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 23 04 4:19 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Hey, I haven't read it, but the most prominently displayed-in-bookstores bardic-type fantasy series I've seen is the Rhapsody trilogy by Elizabeth Haydon.
<br />

<br />
Rhapsody: Child of Blood (Rhapsody Trilogy #1)
<br />
Prophecy: Child of Earth (Rhapsody Trilogy #2)
<br />
Destiny: Child of the Sky (Rhapsody Trilogy #3)
<br />

<br />
Anyone know if these are any good?  I've been thinking about reading them for a long time.
<br />

<br />
But, as far as the fantasy I've read goes, every good series at least touches upon the importance of song and verse, because that was historically the main mode of passing down oral traditions, and it was great entertainment at the same time.  For a fantasy series (not sci-fi, since that's intentionally different, which is also why I don't like it  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" />) to be good, it's GOT to have at least some music in it.
<br />

<br />
I love the wheel of time, and there is a little in it, as mentioned, but not a ton.  In the Lord of the Rings, the only perfect fantasy I've ever read (of course, tolkien invented the genre basically!), song and verse were very important.  The elves are constantly singing, and both humans and halflings place a premium on it as well.  And when you get back into the Silmarillion and such, wow, verse is so often prophetic and important, just like it is in most of the world's mythologies.  Song is key to every culture; it's a necessity in fantasy.
<br />

<br />
But anyway, I could talk about that all day <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-10.gif" border="0" alt="Blushing" hspace="2" />.  Anyone know anything about Haydon?
<br />

<br />
Elbereth 65 bard cazic
<br />

<br />
**Edit, dumb typos**</span></td>
